<paragraph blockId="72.[163,1072,546,749]" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">
R e c o g n i t i o n The female of 
<taxonomicName box="[566,785,581,602]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ammophila" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="72" pageNumber="455" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leclercqi">
<emphasis box="[566,785,581,602]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">Ammophila leclercqi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a gastral apex black without a metallic shine, the supra-antennal lamellate projection absent, the mesothoracic venter not prominent anteriorly and the episternal sulcus ending at the level of scrobe. Additionally, the arolia are well developed and the claws have a distinct basal tooth (50×). The female of 
<taxonomicName box="[387,504,698,719]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ammophila" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="72" pageNumber="455" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leclercqi">
<emphasis box="[387,504,698,719]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">A. leclercqi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[642,775,698,719]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ammophila" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="72" pageNumber="455" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hungarica">
<emphasis box="[642,775,698,719]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">A. hungarica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having a short and thick petiole and tergum I.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[163,694,764,786]" box="[163,694,764,786]" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">
Maybe this is an abnorme variation of 
<emphasis box="[554,694,764,786]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">
<taxonomicName box="[554,690,764,786]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ammophila" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="72" pageNumber="455" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hungarica">A. hungarica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[163,1070,801,1175]" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">
D e s c r i p t i o n 
<specimenCount box="[391,412,807,828]" pageId="72" pageNumber="455" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: 
<quantity box="[434,517,801,823]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="72" pageNumber="455" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
. Black except tergum I (except dorsally), gastral segment II (dorsoapically black) and III (basally) red. Clypeus, pronotal lobe, round patch near mesopleural suture, propodeum posterolaterally and mid- and hindcoxa dorsolaterally covered with appressed silvery setae. Erect setae on head and forelegs black, those on thorax and propodeum white. Clypeus slightly elongate, steplike near free margin (
<figureCitation box="[304,384,948,970]" captionStart="Figs 55-65" captionStartId="133.[163,203,1431,1451]" captionTargetBox="[163,1069,204,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-1@133.[163,1070,204,1411]" captionTargetPageId="133" captionText="Figs 55-65: clypeus of female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341146/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
), disk convex (
<figureCitation box="[552,632,948,970]" captionStart="Figs 85-109" captionStartId="136.[163,203,1391,1411]" captionTargetBox="[195,1050,236,1368]" captionTargetId="figure-1@136.[163,1071,204,1371]" captionTargetPageId="136" captionText="Figs 85-109: clypeus of female in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341152/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
). Pronotal collar dull, without transverse striae, scutum also dull, finely, transversely striate anteriorly, obliquely striate posteriorly, admedian line broad, well developed. Scutellum shiny on anterior half, coarsely punctate, longitudinally ridged and punctate on posterior half. Propodeal enclosure obliquely striate and all covered with erect setae. Mesopleuron dull, sparsely punctate anteriorly, obliquely striate posteriorly. Petiole short and thick (
<figureCitation box="[963,1058,1094,1116]" captionStart="Figs 195-197" captionStartId="145.[163,203,1012,1032]" captionTargetBox="[164,1066,204,991]" captionTargetId="figure-1@145.[163,1070,204,992]" captionTargetPageId="145" captionText="Figs 195-197: (195, 196) pronotal collar of female in lateral view; (197) A. leclercqi: petiole and tergum I in dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341171/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">Fig. 197</figureCitation>
). Pronotal collar laterally: 
<figureCitation box="[452,551,1124,1146]" captionStart="Figs 149-160" captionStartId="141.[163,203,1385,1405]" captionTargetBox="[190,1054,227,1365]" captionTargetId="figure-4@141.[163,1069,728,1365]" captionTargetPageId="141" captionText="Figs 149-160: pronotal collar of female in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341163/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="455">Fig. 149</figureCitation>
. Flagellomere I: II=1.6; length of petiole = hindtarsomere I.
</paragraph>
